### Extinct political subdivisions

Beyond the towns that merely transitioned into cities while retaining their original names, the historical landscape of the [South Hampton Roads](/South_Hampton_Roads) area reveals the disappearance of no less than 2 shires, 6 counties, 1 town, and 2 entire cities. A sobering reminder of the impermanence of human constructs, even those etched onto maps. For those undertaking the arduous task of genealogical research, or seeking land and other historical records, it becomes absolutely imperative to consult these old, forgotten names. The past, after all, rarely conforms to present-day convenience.

The following is a comprehensive listing of these 11 extinct shires, counties, towns, and cities, accompanied by their approximate periods of existence:

*   [Elizabeth River Shire](/Elizabeth_River_Shire) (1634–1636) and [Elizabeth City County](/Elizabeth_City_County,_Virginia) (1636–1952)
*   [Warrosquyoake Shire](/Warrosquyoake_Shire) (1634–1637)
*   [New Norfolk County](/New_Norfolk_County) (1636–1637)
*   [Upper Norfolk County](/Upper_Norfolk_County) (1637–1646)
*   [Lower Norfolk County](/Lower_Norfolk_County) (1637–1691)
*   [Nansemond County](/Nansemond_County,_Virginia) (1646–1972)
*   [Norfolk County](/Norfolk_County,_Virginia) (1691–1963)
*   [Princess Anne County](/Princess_Anne_County,_Virginia) (1691–1963)
*   [Town of Berkley](/Berkley,_Virginia) (unknown-1906)
*   [South Norfolk](/South_Norfolk,_Virginia) (1919–1963)
*   [City of Nansemond](/Nansemond,_Virginia) (1972–1974)

### Highways, bridges, tunnels, bridge-tunnels

The [South Hampton Roads](/South_Hampton_Roads) region, characterized by its pervasive aquatic embrace, is largely surrounded by water. This geographical reality necessitates a robust and intricate network of transportation infrastructure. Access from the north is predominantly achieved via a complex system of highways, [bridges](/Bridge), [tunnels](/Tunnel), and the truly remarkable feats of engineering known as [bridge-tunnels](/Bridge-tunnel). These structures span across significant waterways, including the [James](/James_River) and [Elizabeth](/Elizabeth_River_(Virginia)) Rivers, the expansive harbor of [Hampton Roads](/Hampton_Roads) itself, and the iconic [Chesapeake Bay](/Chesapeake_Bay). To the east, the region meets the vast expanse of the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean), while its southern border abuts the State of [North Carolina](/North_Carolina). To the west, it is defined by several counties that are traditionally considered part of the broader [Southside Virginia](/Southside_Virginia) region. It seems humanity is determined to conquer every geographic inconvenience.

